    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#SECir"/>, <citedRange>92</citedRange></bibl> (photo);
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>097000</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Φιλόδαμος">Φιλό<supplied reason="lost">δ</supplied>αμος</name> 
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name type="patronymic" nymRef="#Σάτυρος">Σ<supplied reason="undefined" evidence="previouseditor">α</supplied><unclear>τ</unclear><supplied reason="undefined" evidence="previouseditor">ύ</supplied>ρου</name></persName></persName>
                    <lb n="3"/><placeName type="ethnic" nymRef="#Ἀχαιός"><supplied reason="undefined" evidence="previouseditor">Ἀχ</supplied>αιός</placeName>
                </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p><app loc="1"><rdg resp="#SECir">Φιλό<unclear>δ</unclear>αμος</rdg>
                </app>
                <app loc="2"><rdg resp="#SECir">Σα<unclear>τ</unclear>ύρου</rdg>
                </app>
                <app loc="3"><rdg resp="#SECir"><unclear>Ἀχ</unclear>αιός</rdg>
                </app>
                </p>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Philodamos fils de Satyros, achéen.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
               <p>Philodamos son of Satyros, an Achaean.</p> 
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
               <p>Philodamos figlio di Satyros, acheo.</p> 
            </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Although Oliverio's photograph does not show the stone in a better condition than that of 1977, his readings were validated by Pugliese Carratelli
                    (<bibl><ptr target="#SECir"/>, <citedRange>92</citedRange></bibl>), who saw the stone in 1960. We thus accept their readings for the father's name (a quite common name in Achaia) and
                the ethnic.</p>
          	<p>The ethnic 'Achaean' supposes a terminus post quem in 280 BC.</p> 
	<p/>
            </div></body>
